Surprisingly hard to accurately rate:  I was divided between 3.5 and 4.5 stars.  The standout is clearly the value:  their current 2020 special is insane (burrito, chips, and a cookie for $9 all day), and the regular portions and prices are very reasonable as well.  My chicken burrito, cookie, and chips were good but not great:  definitely tasty but closer to the level of a Chipotle rather than a high-quality local taqueria.  Chips with spicy queso were a standout side and one that I’ll probably start craving later this week.  All said a well-executed chain concept; it’s definitely worth checking out from the neighborhood!

QDOBA isn't as bad as you think. I don't mean that as a generic "you." I mean You, specifically; the individual reading this, whoever is reading this, whenever they are, past or present. In other words, even if you love QDOBA, it's not as bad as you Don't think it is. If you only like it a little, or think it's mediocre: it's Equally not as bad as you think. And if you Hate it, it's better than you think. It's not so much a medium-paced-food retailer as it is a thought experiment. I can prove it. If you think you like Taco Bell, and that it's some kind of apogee of fast food, you're mistaken in your own opinion: everything at Taco Bell comes out of plastic syringes with big nozzles ordinarily used to artificially inseminate animals. And if you think you like Chipotle, you're also wrong, because all Chipotle employees are rude, and you've never once ordered some chicken there that didn't contain gristle. QDOBA: No Gristle; Not from a Agricultural Recreation Syringe. I'm taking off one-quarter of a star for the quality of what they call their smoked brisket, another for the insufficient pickling of jalapeno slices, and a half-star for refusing to grill a quesadilla with lettuce in it (as a possibly.) Plenty of people enjoy wilted ruffage, and QDOBA Knows it.
